# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: htmx
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] Ajax is not a technology, but rather a programming pattern.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] HTML and CSS can be used in combination to mark up and style information.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] The webpage can be modified by JavaScript to dynamically display (and allow the user to interact with) the new information.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] The built-in XMLHttpRequest object is used to execute Ajax on webpages, allowing websites to load content onto the screen without refreshing the page.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] In the early-to-mid 1990s, most websites were based on complete HTML pages.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] Each user action required a complete new page to be loaded from the server.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] This process was inefficient, as reflected by the user experience: all page content disappeared, then the new page appeared.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] Each time the browser reloaded a page because of a partial change, all the content had to be re-sent, even though only some of the information had changed.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] This placed additional load on the server and made bandwidth a limiting factor in performance.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] The foundations of AJAX originate back in 1996 with the introduction of JavaScript 1.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] Developers quickly discovered that any HTML element which accepted a "src" attribute could be used to fetch remote data.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] By changing the src of a hidden frame, a developer could fetch remote data, process or display it without a page refresh.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] The remote data could be a string, JavaScript code, XML or a partial HTML page generated on the server.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] The same could be done with `<img>` and `<embed>` tags, but many developers were alarmed at the concept of an executable GIF and preferred to use the hidden `<iframe>`.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] This technique was used for both Netscape Navigator and Internet Explorer, the two main browsers at the time, until developers discovered the XMLHTTP server object (MSXML 1.0) was included in Internet Explorer 4.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] Browser detection was then used to either implement the hidden `<iframe>` in Netscape or use the XMLHTTP (MSXML 1.0) object in IE 4.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] In 1996, the iframe tag was introduced by Internet Explorer; like the object element, it can load a part of the web page asynchronously.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] In 1998, the Microsoft Outlook Web Access team developed the concept behind the XMLHttpRequest scripting object.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] It appeared as XMLHTTP in the second version of the MSXML library, which shipped with Internet Explorer 5.0 in March 1999.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] The functionality of the Windows XMLHTTP ActiveX control in IE 5 was later implemented by Mozilla Firefox, Safari, Opera, Google Chrome, and other browsers as the XMLHttpRequest JavaScript object.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] Microsoft adopted the native XMLHttpRequest model as of Internet Explorer 7.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] Support for the ActiveX version remained in Internet Explorer and on "Internet Explorer mode" in Microsoft Edge.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] The utility of these background HTTP requests and asynchronous Web technologies remained fairly obscure until it started appearing in large scale online applications such as Outlook Web Access (2000) and Oddpost (2002).
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] Google made a wide deployment of standards-compliant, cross browser Ajax with Gmail (2004) and Google Maps (2005).
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] In October 2004 Kayak.com's public beta release was among the first large-scale e-commerce uses of what their developers at that time called "the xml http thing".
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] This increased interest in Ajax among web program developers.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] The term *AJAX* was publicly used on 18 February 2005 by Jesse James Garrett in an article titled *Ajax: A New Approach to Web Applications*, based on techniques used on Google pages.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] On 5 April 2006, the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) released the first draft specification for the XMLHttpRequest object in an attempt to create an official Web standard.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] The latest draft of the XMLHttpRequest object was published on 6 October 2016, and the XMLHttpRequest specification is now a living standard.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] The term *Ajax* has come to represent a broad group of Web technologies that can be used to implement a Web application that communicates with a server in the background, without interfering with the current state of the page.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] Since then, however, there have been a number of developments in the technologies used in an Ajax application, and in the definition of the term Ajax itself.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] XML is no longer required for data interchange and, therefore, XSLT is no longer required for the manipulation of data.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) is often used as an alternative format for data interchange, although other formats such as preformatted HTML or plain text can also be used.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] A variety of popular JavaScript libraries, including jQuery, include abstractions to assist in executing Ajax requests.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] An example of a simple Ajax request using the GET method, written in JavaScript.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] Ajax offers several benefits that can significantly enhance web application performance and user experience.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] By reducing server traffic and improving speed, Ajax plays a crucial role in modern web development.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] One key advantage of Ajax is its capacity to render web applications without requiring data retrieval, resulting in reduced server traffic.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] This optimization minimizes response times on both the server and client sides, eliminating the need for users to endure loading screens.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] Furthermore, Ajax facilitates asynchronous processing by simplifying the utilization of XmlHttpRequest, which enables efficient handling of requests for asynchronous data retrieval.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] Additionally, the dynamic loading of content enhances the application's performance significantly.
[src:htmx/ajax-programming] Besides, Ajax enjoys broad support across all major web browsers, including Microsoft Internet Explorer versions 5 and above, Mozilla Firefox versions 1.0 and beyond, Opera versions 7.6 and above, and Apple Safari versions 1.2 and higher.
[src:htmx/examples] A list of GitHub repositories showing examples of integration with a wide variety of server-side languages and platforms, including JavaScript, Python, Java, and many others.
[src:htmx/examples] Below are a set of UX patterns implemented in htmx with minimal HTML and styling.
[src:htmx/examples] You can copy and paste them and then adjust them for your needs.
[src:htmx/examples] For common practices see the Hotwire / Turbo to htmx Migration Guide.
[src:htmx/htmx] The library supports communication with the server using standard HTTP methods and simplifies inserting server responses (usually text or HTML fragments) into designated parts of the web page without having to redraw the entire page.
[src:htmx/htmx] This in turn allows for similar behavior to what can be achieved with reconciliation behavior in virtual DOMs.
[src:htmx/htmx] htmx has its roots in intercooler.js, a frontend library created by Carson Gross in 2013.
[src:htmx/htmx] The library aimed to address the complexity associated with AJAX (asynchronous JavaScript and XML) by introducing a simplified approach using HTML attributes.
[src:htmx/htmx] The intent was to create a framework that was aligned with Roy Fielding's original intent for REST (representational state transfer) - and specifically HATEOAS (hypermedia as the engine of application state).
[src:htmx/htmx] The problem is described in Fielding's blog post "REST APIs must be hypertext-driven" from October 2008.
[src:htmx/htmx] htmx was created as an improved version of intercooler.js that did not rely on jQuery with version 1.0.0 being released in November 2020.
[src:htmx/htmx] The release of htmx was a significant milestone for the project, by offering a way to utilize AJAX, CSS transitions, WebSockets, and Server-Sent Events directly in HTML using attributes.
[src:htmx/htmx] In 2023, htmx was added to the first cohort of the GitHub Accelerator program, a program that provides open source projects with funding and guidance from members of mature open source projects.
[src:htmx/htmx] htmx combines the capabilities of modern frameworks with the server-side processing of traditional web applications.
[src:htmx/htmx] This allows the library to avoid issues with large bundles, complex state management, and hydration.
[src:htmx/htmx] This approach offers a more accessible and intuitive way to build modern user interfaces while avoiding the complexities often associated with traditional JavaScript frameworks.
[src:htmx/htmx] As htmx can update specific parts of a webpage without the need to reload the entire page, as would be the case with plain HTML and CSS, using it might result in improved user experience and performance, since only a part of the data needs to be re-fetched from the server.
[src:htmx/htmx] The library also challenges the common approach of utilizing JSON as the standard payload for HTTP requests by replacing it with HTML.
[src:htmx/htmx] htmx adds custom attributes to HTML to define dynamic behavior such as triggering server requests and updating content.
[src:htmx/htmx] The functionality of htmx is built off of the attributes `hx-get`, `hx-post`, `hx-put`, `hx-delete`, and`hx-patch`, which issue AJAX requests with the specified HTTP method.
[src:htmx/htmx] These requests are made when a certain DOM event is fired: `change` for input, select, and textarea elements; `submit` for form elements; and `click` for other elements.
[src:htmx/htmx] The event can also be overridden with `hx-trigger`.
[src:htmx/htmx] Other attributes include `hx-target` for specifying a target other than the current element for swapping content into and `hx-swap` for setting how the content fetched from the server should be swapped or placed relative to the target element.
[src:htmx/htmx] Since its inception as intercooler.js and its subsequent evolution into htmx, the library has gained a significant following within the web development community. htmx has been viewed as a simpler and lighter weight alternative to full-blown JavaScript frameworks like React, Vue.js, and Angular.
[src:htmx/htmx] As a result, it has gained a measure of popularity as an alternative to the approach used by most JavaScript frameworks for building dynamic web applications.
[src:htmx/htmx] htmx integrations have been developed for various full-stack/backend web frameworks, programming languages and templating engines, including Node.js, Django, Flask, Adobe ColdFusion, ASP.NET, Java, Clojure, and Ruby on Rails.
[src:htmx/htmx] Such libraries are usually a matter of nothing more than convenience since htmx's portable and minimalist design allows it to be integrated with virtually any HTML templating engine.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] include the representation data in the body.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following is a request with no body.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:htmx/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:htmx/page-p01] htmx is a library that allows you to access modern browser features directly from HTML, rather than using javascript.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Note that when you are using htmx, on the server side you typically respond with *HTML*, not *JSON*.
[src:htmx/page-p01] This keeps you firmly within the original web programming model, using Hypertext As The Engine Of Application State without even needing to really understand that concept.
[src:htmx/page-p01] If you understand the concepts around htmx and want to see the quirks of the library, please see our QUIRKS page.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Version 1 of htmx is still supported and supports IE11, but the latest version of htmx is 2.x.
[src:htmx/page-p01] If you are migrating to htmx 2.x from htmx 1.x, please see the htmx 1.x migration guide.
[src:htmx/page-p01] If you are migrating to htmx from intercooler.js, please see the intercooler migration guide.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Htmx is a dependency-free, browser-oriented javascript library.
[src:htmx/page-p01] This means that using it is as simple as adding a `<script>` tag to your document head.
[src:htmx/page-p01] There is no need for a build system to use it.
[src:htmx/page-p01] The fastest way to get going with htmx is to load it via a CDN.
[src:htmx/page-p01] While the CDN approach is extremely simple, you may want to consider not using CDNs in production.
[src:htmx/page-p01] The next easiest way to install htmx is to simply copy it into your project.
[src:htmx/page-p01] After installing, you’ll need to use appropriate tooling to use `node_modules/htmx.org/dist/htmx.js` (or `.min.js`).
[src:htmx/page-p01] For example, you might bundle htmx with some extensions and project-specific code.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Each of these attributes takes a URL to issue an AJAX request to.
[src:htmx/page-p01] If you want different behavior you can use the hx-trigger attribute to specify which event will cause the request.
[src:htmx/page-p01] A trigger can also have a few additional modifiers that change its behavior.
[src:htmx/page-p01] This input will issue a request 500 milliseconds after a key up event if the input has been changed and inserts the results into the `div` with the id `search-results`.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Multiple triggers can be specified in the hx-trigger attribute, separated by commas.
[src:htmx/page-p01] You may also apply trigger filters by using square brackets after the event name, enclosing a javascript expression that will be evaluated.
[src:htmx/page-p01] If the expression evaluates to `true` the event will trigger, otherwise it will not.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Properties like `ctrlKey` will be resolved against the triggering event first, then against the global scope.
[src:htmx/page-p01] The `this` symbol will be set to the current element.
[src:htmx/page-p01] You can also use custom events to trigger requests if you have an advanced use case.
[src:htmx/page-p01] If you want to stop polling from a server response you can respond with the HTTP response code `286` and the element will cancel the polling.
[src:htmx/page-p01] If the `/messages` end point keeps returning a div set up this way, it will keep “polling” back to the URL every second.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Load polling can be useful in situations where a poll has an end point at which point the polling terminates, such as when you are showing the user a progress bar.
[src:htmx/page-p01] When an AJAX request is issued it is often good to let the user know that something is happening since the browser will not give them any feedback.
[src:htmx/page-p01] You can accomplish this in htmx by using `htmx-indicator` class.
[src:htmx/page-p01] The `htmx-indicator` class is defined so that the opacity of any element with this class is 0 by default, making it invisible but present in the DOM.
[src:htmx/page-p01] When htmx issues a request, it will put a `htmx-request` class onto an element (either the requesting element or another element, if specified).
[src:htmx/page-p01] The `htmx-request` class will cause a child element with the `htmx-indicator` class on it to transition to an opacity of 1, showing the indicator.
[src:htmx/page-p01] When it is clicked the `htmx-request` class will be added to it, which will reveal the spinner gif element.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Here we call out the indicator explicitly by id.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Note that we could have placed the class on the parent `div` as well and had the same effect.
[src:htmx/page-p01] You can also add the `disabled` attribute to elements for the duration of a request by using the hx-disabled-elt attribute.
[src:htmx/page-p01] If you want the response to be loaded into a different element other than the one that made the request, you can use the hx-target attribute, which takes a CSS selector.
[src:htmx/page-p01] You can see that the results from the search are going to be loaded into `div#search-results`, rather than into the input tag.
[src:htmx/page-p01] In addition, a CSS selector may be wrapped in `<` and `/>` characters, mimicking the query literal syntax of hyperscript.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Relative targets like this can be useful for creating flexible user interfaces without peppering your DOM with lots of `id` attributes.
[src:htmx/page-p01] htmx offers a few different ways to swap the HTML returned into the DOM.
[src:htmx/page-p01] By default, the content replaces the `innerHTML` of the target element.
[src:htmx/page-p01] In addition to the standard swap mechanisms above, htmx also supports *morphing* swaps, via extensions.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Morphing swaps attempt to *merge* new content into the existing DOM, rather than simply replacing it.
[src:htmx/page-p01] They often do a better job preserving things like focus, video state, etc. by mutating existing nodes in-place during the swap operation, at the cost of more CPU.
[src:htmx/page-p01] The new, experimental View Transitions API gives developers a way to create an animated transition between different DOM states.
[src:htmx/page-p01] It is still in active development and is not available in all browsers, but htmx provides a way to work with this new API that falls back to the non-transition mechanism if the API is not available in a given browser.
[src:htmx/page-p01] View Transitions can be configured using CSS, as outlined in the Chrome documentation for the feature.
[src:htmx/page-p01] You can see a view transition example on the Animation Examples page.
[src:htmx/page-p01] The hx-swap attribute supports many options for tuning the swapping behavior of htmx.
[src:htmx/page-p01] For example, by default htmx will swap in the title of a title tag found anywhere in the new content.
[src:htmx/page-p01] All swap modifiers appear after the swap style is specified, and are colon-separated.
[src:htmx/page-p01] See the hx-swap documentation for more details on these options.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Often you want to coordinate the requests between two elements.
[src:htmx/page-p01] For example, you may want a request from one element to supersede the request of another element, or to wait until the other element’s request has finished.
[src:htmx/page-p01] htmx offers a `hx-sync` attribute to help you accomplish this.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Without using `hx-sync`, filling out the input and immediately submitting the form triggers two parallel requests to `/validate` and `/store`.
[src:htmx/page-p01] This resolves the synchronization between the two elements in a declarative way.
[src:htmx/page-p01] More examples and details can be found on the `hx-sync` attribute page.
[src:htmx/page-p01] htmx makes it easy to use CSS Transitions without javascript.
[src:htmx/page-p01] When htmx swaps in this new content, it will do so in such a way that the CSS transition will apply to the new content, giving you a nice, smooth transition to the new state.
[src:htmx/page-p01] So, in summary, all you need to do to use CSS transitions for an element is keep its `id` stable across requests!
[src:htmx/page-p01] You can see the Animation Examples for more details and live demonstrations.
[src:htmx/page-p01] To understand how CSS transitions actually work in htmx, you must understand the underlying swap & settle model that htmx uses.
[src:htmx/page-p01] When new content is received from a server, before the content is swapped in, the existing content of the page is examined for elements that match by the `id` attribute.
[src:htmx/page-p01] If a match is found for an element in the new content, the attributes of the old content are copied onto the new element before the swap occurs.
[src:htmx/page-p01] The new content is then swapped in, but with the *old* attribute values.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Finally, the new attribute values are swapped in, after a “settle” delay (20ms by default).
[src:htmx/page-p01] A little crazy, but this is what allows CSS transitions to work without any javascript by the developer.
[src:htmx/page-p01] In this response, `div#message` would be swapped directly into the matching DOM element, while the additional content would be swapped into the target in the normal manner.
[src:htmx/page-p01] You can use this technique to “piggy-back” updates on other requests.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Table elements can be problematic when combined with out of band swaps, because, by the HTML spec, many can’t stand on their own in the DOM (e.g.
[src:htmx/page-p01] If you want to select a subset of the response HTML to swap into the target, you can use the hx-select attribute, which takes a CSS selector and selects the matching elements from the response.
[src:htmx/page-p01] You can also pick out pieces of content for an out-of-band swap by using the hx-select-oob attribute, which takes a list of element IDs to pick out and swap.
[src:htmx/page-p01] If there is content that you wish to be preserved across swaps (e.g. a video player that you wish to remain playing even if a swap occurs) you can use the hx-preserve attribute on the elements you wish to be preserved.
[src:htmx/page-p01] By default, an element that causes a request will include its value if it has one.
[src:htmx/page-p01] If the element is a form it will include the values of all inputs within it.
[src:htmx/page-p01] As with HTML forms, the `name` attribute of the input is used as the parameter name in the request that htmx sends.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Additionally, if the element causes a non-`GET` request, the values of all the inputs of the associated form will be included (typically this is the nearest enclosing form, but could be different if e.g.
[src:htmx/page-p01] `<button form="associated-form">` is used).
[src:htmx/page-p01] If you wish to include the values of other elements, you can use the hx-include attribute with a CSS selector of all the elements whose values you want to include in the request.
[src:htmx/page-p01] If you wish to filter out some parameters you can use the hx-params attribute.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Finally, if you want to programmatically modify the parameters, you can use the htmx:configRequest event.
[src:htmx/page-p01] If you wish to upload files via an htmx request, you can set the hx-encoding attribute to `multipart/form-data`.
[src:htmx/page-p01] This will use a `FormData` object to submit the request, which will properly include the file in the request.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Note that depending on your server-side technology, you may have to handle requests with this type of body content very differently.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Note that htmx fires a `htmx:xhr:progress` event periodically based on the standard `progress` event during upload, which you can hook into to show the progress of the upload.
[src:htmx/page-p01] See the examples section for more advanced form patterns, including progress bars and error handling.
[src:htmx/page-p01] You can include extra values in a request using the hx-vals (name-expression pairs in JSON format) and hx-vars attributes (comma-separated name-expression pairs that are dynamically computed).
[src:htmx/page-p01] Using events you can implement more sophisticated confirmation dialogs.
[src:htmx/page-p01] The confirm example shows how to use sweetalert2 library for confirmation of htmx actions.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Another option to do confirmation with is via the `htmx:confirm` event.
[src:htmx/page-p01] This event is fired on *every* trigger for a request (not just on elements that have a `hx-confirm` attribute) and can be used to implement asynchronous confirmation of the request.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Most attributes in htmx are inherited: they apply to the element they are on as well as any children elements.
[src:htmx/page-p01] This allows you to “hoist” attributes up the DOM to avoid code duplication.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Here we have a duplicate `hx-confirm` attribute.
[src:htmx/page-p01] This `hx-confirm` attribute will now apply to all htmx-powered elements within it.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Sometimes you wish to undo this inheritance.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Consider if we had a cancel button to this group, but didn’t want it to be confirmed.
[src:htmx/page-p01] The top two buttons would then show a confirm dialog, but the bottom cancel button would not.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Inheritance can be disabled on a per-element and per-attribute basis using the `hx-disinherit` attribute.
[src:htmx/page-p01] If you wish to disable attribute inheritance entirely, you can set the `htmx.config.disableInheritance` configuration variable to `true`.
[src:htmx/page-p01] This will disable inheritance as a default, and allow you to specify inheritance explicitly with the `hx-inherit` attribute.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Htmx supports “boosting” regular HTML anchors and forms with the hx-boost attribute.
[src:htmx/page-p01] This attribute will convert all anchor tags and forms into AJAX requests that, by default, target the body of the page.
[src:htmx/page-p01] The anchor tag in this div will issue an AJAX `GET` request to `/blog` and swap the response into the `body` tag.
[src:htmx/page-p01] A feature of `hx-boost` is that it degrades gracefully if javascript is not enabled: the links and forms continue to work, they simply don’t use ajax requests.
[src:htmx/page-p01] This is known as Progressive Enhancement, and it allows a wider audience to use your site’s functionality.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Other htmx patterns can be adapted to achieve progressive enhancement as well, but they will require more thought.
[src:htmx/page-p01] As it is written, it will not degrade gracefully: someone who does not have javascript enabled will not be able to use this feature.
[src:htmx/page-p01] This is done for simplicity’s sake, to keep the example as brief as possible.
[src:htmx/page-p01] With this in place, javascript-enabled clients would still get the nice active-search UX, but non-javascript enabled clients would be able to hit the enter key and still search.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Even better, you could add a “Search” button as well.
[src:htmx/page-p01] You would then need to update the form with an `hx-post` that mirrored the `action` attribute, or perhaps use `hx-boost` on it.
[src:htmx/page-p01] You would need to check on the server side for the `HX-Request` header to differentiate between an htmx-driven and a regular request, to determine exactly what to render to the client.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Other patterns can be adapted similarly to achieve the progressive enhancement needs of your application.
[src:htmx/page-p01] As you can see, this requires more thought and more work.
[src:htmx/page-p01] It also rules some functionality entirely out of bounds.
[src:htmx/page-p01] These tradeoffs must be made by you, the developer, with respect to your projects goals and audience.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Accessibility is a concept closely related to progressive enhancement.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Using progressive enhancement techniques such as `hx-boost` will make your htmx application more accessible to a wide array of users.
[src:htmx/page-p01] htmx-based applications are very similar to normal, non-AJAX driven web applications because htmx is HTML-oriented.
[src:htmx/page-p01] As such, the normal HTML accessibility recommendations apply.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Web Sockets and Server Sent Events (SSE) are supported via extensions.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Please see the SSE extension and WebSocket extension pages to learn more.
[src:htmx/page-p01] When a user clicks on this link, htmx will snapshot the current DOM and store it before it makes a request to /blog.
[src:htmx/page-p01] It then does the swap and pushes a new location onto the history stack.
[src:htmx/page-p01] When a user hits the back button, htmx will retrieve the old content from storage and swap it back into the target, simulating “going back” to the previous state.
[src:htmx/page-p01] If the location is not found in the cache, htmx will make an ajax request to the given URL, with the header `HX-History-Restore-Request` set to true, and expects back the HTML needed for the entire page.
[src:htmx/page-p01] You should always set `htmx.config.historyRestoreAsHxRequest` to false to prevent the `HX-Request` header which can then be safely used to respond with partials.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Alternatively, if the `htmx.config.refreshOnHistoryMiss` config variable is set to true, it will issue a hard browser refresh.
[src:htmx/page-p01] By default, htmx will use the `body` to take and restore the history snapshot from.
[src:htmx/page-p01] This is usually the right thing, but if you want to use a narrower element for snapshotting you can use the hx-history-elt attribute to specify a different one.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Careful: this element will need to be on all pages or restoring from history won’t work reliably.
[src:htmx/page-p01] If you are using a 3rd party library and want to use the htmx history feature, you will need to clean up the DOM before a snapshot is taken.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Let’s consider the Tom Select library, which makes select elements a much richer user experience.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Let’s set up TomSelect to turn any input element with the `.tomselect` class into a rich select element.
[src:htmx/page-p01] This will create a rich selector for all input elements that have the `.tomselect` class on it.
[src:htmx/page-p01] However, it mutates the DOM and we don’t want that mutation saved to the history cache, since TomSelect will be reinitialized when the history content is loaded back into the screen.
[src:htmx/page-p01] This will revert the DOM to the original HTML, thus allowing for a clean snapshot.
[src:htmx/page-p01] History snapshotting can be disabled for a URL by setting the hx-history attribute to `false` on any element in the current document, or any html fragment loaded into the current document by htmx.
[src:htmx/page-p01] This can be used to prevent sensitive data entering the localStorage cache, which can be important for shared-use / public computers.
[src:htmx/page-p01] History navigation will work as expected, but on restoration the URL will be requested from the server instead of the local history cache.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Htmx expects responses to the AJAX requests it makes to be HTML, typically HTML fragments (although a full HTML document, matched with a hx-select tag can be useful too).
[src:htmx/page-p01] Htmx will then swap the returned HTML into the document at the target specified and with the swap strategy specified.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Sometimes you might want to do nothing in the swap, but still perhaps trigger a client side event (see below).
[src:htmx/page-p01] For this situation, by default, you can return a `204 - No Content` response code, and htmx will ignore the content of the response.
[src:htmx/page-p01] In the event of an error response from the server (e.g. a 404 or a 501), htmx will trigger the `htmx:responseError` event, which you can handle.
[src:htmx/page-p01] In the event of a connection error, the `htmx:sendError` event will be triggered.
[src:htmx/page-p01] You can configure the above behavior of htmx by mutating or replacing the `htmx.config.responseHandling` array.
[src:htmx/page-p01] When htmx receives a response it will iterate in order over the `htmx.config.responseHandling` array and test if the `code` property of a given object, when treated as a Regular Expression, matches the current response.
[src:htmx/page-p01] If an entry does match the current response code, it will be used to determine if and how the response will be processed.
[src:htmx/page-p01] As an example of how to use this configuration, consider a situation when a server-side framework responds with a `422 - Unprocessable Entity` response when validation errors occur.
[src:htmx/page-p01] By default, htmx will ignore the response, since it matches the Regular Expression `[45]..`.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Finally, it is worth considering using the Response Targets extension, which allows you to configure the behavior of response codes declaratively via attributes.
[src:htmx/page-p01] When using htmx in a cross origin context, remember to configure your web server to set Access-Control headers in order for htmx headers to be visible on the client side.
[src:htmx/page-p01] See all the request and response headers that htmx implements.
[src:htmx/page-p01] For more on the `HX-Trigger` headers, see `HX-Trigger` Response Headers.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Submitting a form via htmx has the benefit of no longer needing the Post/Redirect/Get Pattern.
[src:htmx/page-p01] After successfully processing a POST request on the server, you don’t need to return a HTTP 302 (Redirect).
[src:htmx/page-p01] You can directly return the new HTML fragment.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Also the response headers above are not provided to htmx for processing with 3xx Redirect response codes like HTTP 302 (Redirect).
[src:htmx/page-p01] Instead, the browser will intercept the redirection internally and return the headers and response from the redirected URL.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Where possible use alternative response codes like 200 to allow returning of these response headers.
[src:htmx/page-p01] You can use the `htmx-swapping` and `htmx-settling` classes to create CSS transitions between pages.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Htmx integrates with the HTML5 Validation API and will not issue a request for a form if a validatable input is invalid.
[src:htmx/page-p01] This is true for both AJAX requests as well as WebSocket sends.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Non-form elements do not validate before they make requests by default, but you can enable validation by setting the `hx-validate` attribute to “true”.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Normal browser form submission alerts the user of any validation errors automatically and auto focuses on the first invalid input.
[src:htmx/page-p01] For backwards compatibility reasons htmx does not report the validation to the users by default and you should always enable this option by setting `htmx.config.reportValidityOfForms` to `true` to restore the default browser behavior.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Note that all client side validations must be re-done on the server side, as they can always be bypassed.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Htmx allows you to use CSS transitions in many situations using only HTML and CSS.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Please see the Animation Guide for more details on the options available.
[src:htmx/page-p01] htmx provides an extensions mechanism that allows you to customize the libraries’ behavior.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Extensions are defined in javascript and then enabled via the `hx-ext` attribute.
[src:htmx/page-p01] You can see all available extensions on the Extensions page.
[src:htmx/page-p01] The fastest way to install htmx extensions created by others is to load them via a CDN.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Remember to always include the core htmx library before the extensions and enable the extension.
[src:htmx/page-p01] An unminified version is also available at `https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/htmx-ext-extension-name/dist/extension-name.js` (replace `extension-name` with the name of the extension).
[src:htmx/page-p01] While the CDN approach is simple, you may want to consider not using CDNs in production.
[src:htmx/page-p01] The next easiest way to install htmx extensions is to simply copy them into your project.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Download the extension from `https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/htmx-ext-extension-name` (replace `extension-name` with the name of the extension) e.g., https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/htmx-ext-response-targets.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Then add it to the appropriate directory in your project and include it where necessary with a `<script>` tag.
[src:htmx/page-p01] After installing, you’ll need to use appropriate tooling to bundle `node_modules/htmx-ext-extension-name/dist/extension-name.js` (or `.min.js`).
[src:htmx/page-p01] For example, you might bundle the extension with htmx core from `node_modules/htmx.org/dist/htmx.js` and project-specific code.
[src:htmx/page-p01] If you are using a bundler to manage your javascript (e.g.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Note: Idiomorph does not follow the naming convention of htmx extensions.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Use `idiomorph` instead of `htmx-ext-idiomorph`.
[src:htmx/page-p01] For example, `https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/idiomorph` or `npm install idiomorph`.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Note: Community extensions hosted outside this repository might have different installation instructions.
[src:htmx/page-p01] Please check the corresponding repository for set-up guidance.
[src:htmx/page-p01] To enable an extension, add a `hx-ext="extension-name"` attribute to `<body>` or another HTML element (replace `extension-name` with the name of the extension).
[src:htmx/page-p01] The extension will be applied to all child elements.
[src:htmx/page-p01] The following example shows how to enable response-targets extension, allowing you to specify different target elements to be swapped based on HTTP response code.
[src:htmx/page-p01] If you are interested in adding your own extension to htmx, please see the extension docs.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Htmx has an extensive events mechanism, which doubles as the logging system.
[src:htmx/page-p02] The `htmx:load` event is fired every time an element is loaded into the DOM by htmx, and is effectively the equivalent to the normal `load` event.
[src:htmx/page-p02] This does the same thing as the first example, but is a little cleaner.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Here we add a parameter and header to the request before it is sent.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Here we handle a few 400-level error response codes that would normally not do a swap in htmx.
[src:htmx/page-p02] So, for example, you can listen for `htmx:afterSwap` or for `htmx:after-swap`.
[src:htmx/page-p02] This facilitates interoperability with other libraries.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Alpine.js, for example, requires kebab case.
[src:htmx/page-p02] If you set a logger at `htmx.logger`, every event will be logged.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Declarative and event driven programming with htmx (or any other declarative language) can be a wonderful and highly productive activity, but one disadvantage when compared with imperative approaches is that it can be trickier to debug.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Figuring out why something *isn’t* happening, for example, can be difficult if you don’t know the tricks.
[src:htmx/page-p02] The first debugging tool you can use is the `htmx.logAll()` method.
[src:htmx/page-p02] This will log every event that htmx triggers and will allow you to see exactly what the library is doing.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Of course, that won’t tell you why htmx *isn’t* doing something.
[src:htmx/page-p02] You might also not know *what* events a DOM element is firing to use as a trigger.
[src:htmx/page-p02] This will spit out all events that are occurring on the element with the id `theElement` to the console, and allow you to see exactly what is going on with it.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Note that this *only* works from the console, you cannot embed it in a script tag on your page.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Finally, push come shove, you might want to just debug `htmx.js` by loading up the unminimized version.
[src:htmx/page-p02] It’s about 2500 lines of javascript, so not an insurmountable amount of code.
[src:htmx/page-p02] You would most likely want to set a break point in the `issueAjaxRequest()` and `handleAjaxResponse()` methods to see what’s going on.
[src:htmx/page-p02] And always feel free to jump on the Discord if you need help.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Sometimes, in order to demonstrate a bug or clarify a usage, it is nice to be able to use a javascript snippet site like jsfiddle.
[src:htmx/page-p02] This helper allows you to add mock responses by adding `template` tags with a `url` attribute to indicate which URL.
[src:htmx/page-p02] The response for that url will be the innerHTML of the template, making it easy to construct mock responses.
[src:htmx/page-p02] You may embed simple expressions in the template with the `${}` syntax.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Note that this should only be used for demos and is in no way guaranteed to work for long periods of time as it will always be grabbing the latest versions htmx and hyperscript!
[src:htmx/page-p02] While htmx encourages a hypermedia approach to building web applications, it offers many options for client scripting.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Scripting is included in the REST-ful description of web architecture, see: Code-On-Demand.
[src:htmx/page-p02] The primary integration point between htmx and scripting solutions is the events that htmx sends and can respond to.
[src:htmx/page-p02] See the SortableJS example in the 3rd Party Javascript section for a good template for integrating a JavaScript library with htmx via events.
[src:htmx/page-p02] We have an entire chapter entitled “Client-Side Scripting” in our book that looks at how scripting can be integrated into your htmx-based application.
[src:htmx/page-p02] This feature allows scripting logic to be co-located with the HTML elements the logic applies to, giving good Locality of Behaviour (LoB).
[src:htmx/page-p02] Unfortunately, HTML only allows `on*` attributes for a fixed number of specific DOM events (e.g.
[src:htmx/page-p02] `onclick`) and doesn’t provide a generalized mechanism for responding to arbitrary events on elements.
[src:htmx/page-p02] In order to address this shortcoming, htmx offers `hx-on*` attributes.
[src:htmx/page-p02] These attributes allow you to respond to any event in a manner that preserves the LoB of the standard `on*` properties.
[src:htmx/page-p02] So, the string `hx-on`, followed by a colon (or a dash), then by the name of the event.
[src:htmx/page-p02] For a `click` event, of course, we would recommend sticking with the standard `onclick` attribute.
[src:htmx/page-p02] However, consider an htmx-powered button that wishes to add a parameter to a request using the `htmx:config-request` event.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Here the `example` parameter is added to the `POST` request before it is issued, with the value ‘Hello Scripting!’.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Another usecase is to reset user input on successful requests using the `afterRequest` event, avoiding the need for something like an out of band swap.
[src:htmx/page-p02] The `hx-on*` attributes are a very simple mechanism for generalized embedded scripting.
[src:htmx/page-p02] It is *not* a replacement for more fully developed front-end scripting solutions such as AlpineJS or hyperscript.
[src:htmx/page-p02] It can, however, augment a VanillaJS-based approach to scripting in your htmx-powered application.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Note that HTML attributes are *case insensitive*.
[src:htmx/page-p02] This means that, unfortunately, events that rely on capitalization/ camel casing, cannot be responded to.
[src:htmx/page-p02] If you need to support camel case events we recommend using a more fully functional scripting solution such as AlpineJS or hyperscript. htmx dispatches all its events in both camelCase and in kebab-case for this very reason.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Htmx integrates fairly well with third party libraries.
[src:htmx/page-p02] If the library fires events on the DOM, you can use those events to trigger requests from htmx.
[src:htmx/page-p02] With Sortable, as with most javascript libraries, you need to initialize content at some point.
[src:htmx/page-p02] This will ensure that as new content is added to the DOM by htmx, sortable elements are properly initialized.
[src:htmx/page-p02] If javascript adds content to the DOM that has htmx attributes on it, you need to make sure that this content is initialized with the `htmx.process()` function.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Some 3rd party libraries create content from HTML template elements.
[src:htmx/page-p02] For instance, Alpine JS uses the `x-if` attribute on templates to add content conditionally.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Such templates are not initially part of the DOM and, if they contain htmx attributes, will need a call to `htmx.process()` after they are loaded.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Please see the Web Components Examples page for examples on how to integrate htmx with web components.
[src:htmx/page-p02] htmx works with standard HTTP caching mechanisms out of the box.
[src:htmx/page-p02] If your server adds the `Last-Modified` HTTP response header to the response for a given URL, the browser will automatically add the `If-Modified-Since` request HTTP header to the next requests to the same URL.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Be mindful that if your server can render different content for the same URL depending on some other headers, you need to use the `Vary` response HTTP header.
[src:htmx/page-p02] For example, if your server renders the full HTML when the `HX-Request` header is missing or `false`, and it renders a fragment of that HTML when `HX-Request: true`, you need to add `Vary: HX-Request`.
[src:htmx/page-p02] That causes the cache to be keyed based on a composite of the response URL and the `HX-Request` request header — rather than being based just on the response URL.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Always disable `htmx.config.historyRestoreAsHxRequest` so that these history full HTML requests are not cached with partial fragment responses.
[src:htmx/page-p02] If you are unable (or unwilling) to use the `Vary` header, you can alternatively set the configuration parameter `getCacheBusterParam` to `true`.
[src:htmx/page-p02] If this configuration variable is set, htmx will include a cache-busting parameter in `GET` requests that it makes, which will prevent browsers from caching htmx-based and non-htmx based responses in the same cache slot.
[src:htmx/page-p02] htmx also works with `ETag` as expected.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Be mindful that if your server can render different content for the same URL (for example, depending on the value of the `HX-Request` header), the server needs to generate a different `ETag` for each content.
[src:htmx/page-p02] htmx allows you to define logic directly in your DOM.
[src:htmx/page-p02] This has a number of advantages, the largest being Locality of Behavior, which makes your system easier to understand and maintain.
[src:htmx/page-p02] A concern with this approach, however, is security: since htmx increases the expressiveness of HTML, if a malicious user is able to inject HTML into your application, they can leverage this expressiveness of htmx to malicious ends.
[src:htmx/page-p02] The first rule of HTML-based web development has always been: *do not trust input from the user*.
[src:htmx/page-p02] You should escape all 3rd party, untrusted content that is injected into your site.
[src:htmx/page-p02] This is to prevent, among other issues, XSS attacks.
[src:htmx/page-p02] There is extensive documentation on XSS and how to prevent it on the excellent OWASP Website, including a Cross Site Scripting Prevention Cheat Sheet.
[src:htmx/page-p02] The good news is that this is a very old and well understood topic, and the vast majority of server-side templating languages support automatic escaping of content to prevent just such an issue.
[src:htmx/page-p02] That being said, there are times people choose to inject HTML more dangerously, often via some sort of `raw()` mechanism in their templating language.
[src:htmx/page-p02] This can be done for good reasons, but if the content being injected is coming from a 3rd party then it *must* be scrubbed, including removing attributes starting with `hx-` and `data-hx`, as well as inline `<script>` tags, etc.
[src:htmx/page-p02] If you are injecting raw HTML and doing your own escaping, a best practice is to *whitelist* the attributes and tags you allow, rather than to blacklist the ones you disallow.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Of course, bugs happen and developers are not perfect, so it is good to have a layered approach to security for your web application, and htmx provides tools to help secure your application as well.
[src:htmx/page-p02] The first tool htmx provides to help further secure your application is the `hx-disable` attribute.
[src:htmx/page-p02] This attribute will prevent processing of all htmx attributes on a given element, and on all elements within it.
[src:htmx/page-p02] And htmx will not process any htmx-related attributes or features found in that content.
[src:htmx/page-p02] This attribute cannot be disabled by injecting further content: if an `hx-disable` attribute is found anywhere in the parent hierarchy of an element, it will not be processed by htmx.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Another security consideration is htmx history cache.
[src:htmx/page-p02] You may have pages that have sensitive data that you do not want stored in the users `localStorage` cache.
[src:htmx/page-p02] You can omit a given page from the history cache by including the `hx-history` attribute anywhere on the page, and setting its value to `false`.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Note that all features removed by disabling `eval()` can be reimplemented using your own custom javascript and the htmx event model.
[src:htmx/page-p02] If you want to allow requests to some domains beyond the current host, but not leave things totally open, you can use the `htmx:validateUrl` event.
[src:htmx/page-p02] This event will have the request URL available in the `detail.url` slot, as well as a `sameHost` property.
[src:htmx/page-p02] You can inspect these values and, if the request is not valid, invoke `preventDefault()` on the event to prevent the request from being issued.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Browsers also provide tools for further securing your web application.
[src:htmx/page-p02] The most powerful tool available is a Content Security Policy.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Using a CSP you can tell the browser to, for example, not issue requests to non-origin hosts, to not evaluate inline script tags, etc.
[src:htmx/page-p02] This tells the browser “Only allow connections to the original (source) domain”.
[src:htmx/page-p02] This would be redundant with the `htmx.config.selfRequestsOnly`, but a layered approach to security is warranted and, in fact, ideal, when dealing with application security.
[src:htmx/page-p02] A full discussion of CSPs is beyond the scope of this document, but the MDN Article provides a good jumping-off point for exploring this topic.
[src:htmx/page-p02] The assignment and checking of CSRF tokens are typically backend responsibilities, but `htmx` can support returning the CSRF token automatically with every request using the `hx-headers` attribute.
[src:htmx/page-p02] The attribute needs to be added to the element issuing the request or one of its ancestor elements.
[src:htmx/page-p02] This makes the `html` and `body` elements effective global vehicles for adding the CSRF token to the `HTTP` request header, as illustrated below.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Note: `hx-boost` does not update the `<html>` or `<body>` tags; if using this feature with `hx-boost`, make sure to include the CSRF token on an element that *will* get replaced.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Many web frameworks support automatically inserting the CSRF token as a hidden input in HTML forms.
[src:htmx/page-p02] The above elements are usually unique in an HTML document and should be easy to locate within templates.
[src:htmx/page-p02] Htmx has some configuration options that can be accessed either programmatically or declaratively.
[src:htmx/page-p02] You can accomplish quite a bit without writing a lot of code!
[src:htmx/reference] The most common attributes when using htmx.
